public class ShutdownHook extends Thread{
    public void run() {
        try {
            new FileOutputStream("D:/saiu.txt").write("OK !".getBytes());
        } catch (Exception e) {}
        System.out.println("SHUT DOWN OK !");
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] a) throws Exception {
        Runtime.getRuntime().addShutdownHook(new ShutdownHook());
        Thread.sleep(50000);
    }
}

Bug.WithStack:
When creating the following class:

public class ShutdownHook extends Thread{
    public void run() {
        try {
            new FileOutputStream("D:/saiu.txt").write("OK !".getBytes());
        } catch (Exception e) {}
        System.out.println("SHUT DOWN OK !");
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] a) throws Exception {
        Runtime.getRuntime().addShutdownHook(new ShutdownHook());
        Thread.sleep(50000);
    }
}

And run, when the "STOP" button is pressed on the Console View, the file is not 
created neither the message "SHUT DOWN OK !" displayed.

This is certainly a bug.
I'm not sure where you create this class or run the main method but I just tried
this by dropping your class into a plugin in Eclipse and calling the main
method, then exiting eclipse.  The shutdown was run on exit.  Please re-open if
you have more steps to recreate.

